	<h3><a name="familyinfo">How can I find information about a particular RNA family?</a></h3>

	<p>
You can do this in several ways. If you already know the Rfam
accession or name of the family you can use the "jump to" boxes on
home page or most pages of the website. Alternatively if your not sure
of the family accession or correct name and want to guess you should
use the "keyword" search box in the header of each page. This search
allows the use of ambiguous terms and will search multiple sections of
the database for a match to your query term. The results page 
will give you a list of all the families with matches and you can
follow the links to the summary page for each family.
</p>
<p>
Alternatively if your not sure of your query term and simply want to
browse our families click on the browse link provided in the header of
every page. This takes you to an index where you can browse the
families. This index sorts the families on their IDs such as
'Rnase_mrp' or '7SK'. You can browse the indexed lists and use either
the ID or accession links to go directly to the family summary page.  
  </p>
	
	<p><a href="#faqTop">back to top</a></p>

	<h3><a name="searchdnaseq">How can I search my DNA sequence for non-coding RNA genes?</a></h3>

	<p> 
Both our single and batch <a
href="http://rfam.sanger.ac.uk/search">sequence searches</a> allow you
to search a nucleotide sequence against the Rfam model library. Any
hits to Rfam families will be returned with start and end coordinates,
orientation and a score for each hit. We suggest you fragment sequences 
into smaller overlapping segments if your sequence is longer than 2 Kbp
and use the 
<a href="http://rfam.sanger.ac.uk/search">batch search</a>
 facility. You might find
this tool for <a href="http://emboss.bioinformatics.nl/cgi-bin/emboss/splitter">splitting
large sequences</a> into fragments useful. Alternatively you can
download and run Rfam locally.

	</p>
	<p><a href="#faqTop">back to top</a></p>


