<h3><a name="downloadalign">How can I view or download a family alignment?</a></h3>

	<p>
From the family summary page, go to the 'Alignments' tab on the left
side panel. The alignment page will give you multiple drop down
options on how to either view or download the sequences for this
family in an aligned or fasta format. The formatting options allow you
to select which type of format you would prefer for the alignment or
the fasta output.
<p>

If the alignment is <i>very</i> large the formatting tool may not be
suitable and we provide the preformatted alignment in Stockholm
format.  A number of Stockholm alignment re-formatters and viewers
exist; Including the sreformat program from the <a
href="http://hmmer.janelia.org">HMMer package</a> and the 
<a href="http://personalpages.manchester.ac.uk/staff/sam.griffiths-jones/software/ralee/">RALEE</a> 
major mode for Emacs.
You can read more about Stockholm format on <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stockholm_format">Wikipedia</a></p>
</p>

<p>
If you are interested downloading alignments for
multiple families you can download all our seed and full alignments in
Stockholm format flatfiles from our <a
href="ftp://ftp.sanger.ac.uk/pub/databases/Rfam/CURRENT">ftp site</a>.
</p>

	<p><a href="#faqTop">back to top</a></p>

<h3><a name="#downloadfasta">How can I download a subset of sequences from a family?</a></h3>

	<p>
Unfortunately, this has not been implemented yet. There are plans in place to adjust the 
underlying Rfam database to allow this. 
	</p>
	<p><a href="#faqTop">back to top</a></p>

<h3><a name="#downloadfastaspecies">How can I download all Rfam sequences for my favourite species?</a></h3>

	<p>
Unfortunately, this has not been implemented yet. These sorts of queries can potentially 
return huge amounts of data, enough to scare our database people about bringing down
servers. There are plans in place to implement a Biomart interface that will allow these
queries. Meanwhile, if you <a href="mailto:rfam-help@sanger.ac.uk">ask us</a> very nicely 
and we have have time then one of our engineers may be able to help. 

The Taxonomy tab on the search page will allow you to
perform taxonomic queries. In fact this function also allows you to
search with queries from internal nodes of the NCBI taxonomic
tree. However, the results are only returned on the family level, not
the sequence level.
	</p>
	<p><a href="#faqTop">back to top</a></p>

<!--other-->

<h3><a name="submitfamily">I would like to submit a family</a></h3>

	<p>
Great! We are very keen for the community to help keep us updated on
new families. Ideally a new family for Rfam should contain elements
(RNA sequences) that have some known functional classification, are
evolutionarily conserved and have evidence for a secondary structure.
The families should not solely be based on prediction only (eg. RNAz,
EvoFold, QRNA predictions) nor solely on transcriptomic data
(eg. tiling array, deep sequencing). For more detailed information on
how to submit a family read this documentation however if you have any
queries please do contact us at <a href="mailto:rfam-help@sanger.ac.uk">Rfam-help@sanger.ac.uk</a>.

If your family is sufficiently interesting or you have several of them then 
you may be interested in publishing your family in the RNA families track
now available through 
<a href="http://www.landesbioscience.com/journals/rnabiology/">RNA Biology.</a>

	</p>
	<p><a href="#faqTop">back to top</a></p>


<h3><a name="editseed">How can I edit a SEED alignment?</a></h3>

	<p>
We do not currently provide public access to edit our alignments. 
This is advantageous in that it maintains our standard of alignments 
and structures. However, if you feel our seed alignment/structure 
annotations can and should be improved please do either contact us,
preferably supplying us with a new alignment in Stockholm format and 
we will do our best to incorporate the improvements.
	</p>
